The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Silicon Valley, Nov. 20 (PTI): A sacked Silicon Valley engineer of Chinese origin has been formally charged with killing his three colleagues, including his Indian American boss, Sid Agarwal.          Jing Hua Wu, 47, a former engineer with SiPort, allegedly shot his colleagues after being fired for poor performance.                   
	 New York (PTI): A US-based Sikh woman, who suffered racial, religious and sexual harassment at work, has won damages after a three-year battle with her former employer. The firm, which had fired Sukhbir Kaur when she complained of discrimination, will pay her and eight other harassment victims $255,000 in damages.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): The Maharashtra government will continue with the ban on Deshdrohi, deputy chief minister R. R. Patil said on Thursday. Kamal Khan, the films producer had met officials in the home department to seek lifting of the ban.                   
	 New Delhi: The cabinet has cleared a central engineering school named after the late Congress leader A.B.A. Ghani Khan Chowdhury in Malda, overriding the finance ministrys concerns that it could be viewed as politically motivated.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Ignou has launched a walk-in-examination scheme under which students can appear for the exam at any test centre instead of waiting for the completion of the six-month term.                   
	 Kathmandu (PTI): A mob threw stones at an Indian diplomats car during anti-Maoist protests in Kathmandu on Thursday. First secretary S.K. Joshi was attacked near the Indian embassy. He was unhurt.                   
	New Delhi (PTI): President Pratibha Patil released a stamp on the late Joachim and Violet Alva on Thursday, coinciding with the centenary year of the freedom-fighter couple. They were the parents-in-law of Margaret Alva.
                                                                                                                         
